Yes, it's possible to solve this problem without recursion or loops by using the binary search algorithm. Here's a Java solution:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    int left = 1, right = n;
    while (left < right) {
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        if (mid * mid == n) {
            right = mid;
        } else if (mid * mid < n) {
            left = mid + 1;
        } else {
            right = mid - 1;
        }
    }
    return left == n;
}
```

This algorithm follows a binary search approach. We initially set `left` as 1 (2^0) and `right` as `n`. In each iteration, we find the middle value `mid` and check if `mid * mid == n`. If it is, we update `right` to `mid`. If not, we adjust our search range to either the left or right half based on the comparison. The loop continues until `left` becomes greater than `right`.

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n), which is much better than the naive recursive approach, which has an exponential time complexity of O(2^n).

